## 2. Data Collection

### What is it?

Data is the fuel for your ML model. Garbage in = garbage out. You need to gather relevant, enough, and trustworthy data.

### Where does data come from?

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Sources of Data] --> B[Your own databases]
    A --> C[Public datasets\nKaggle, UCI, government sites]
    A --> D[Web scraping\nCollect from websites]
    A --> E[APIs\nTwitter, weather, stocks]
    A --> F[Surveys / manual entry]
    A --> G[Sensors / IoT devices]
```

### Real-World Example

For the pizza shop problem:
- **Sales records** from your POS system (date, qty sold)
- **Weather data** from a free API (rainy days = more delivery orders?)
- **Holiday calendar** (Fridays are busier)
- **Promotions history** (did a discount run that day?)

### What makes good data?

| Property | What it means | Why it matters |
|----------|--------------|----------------|
| **Relevant** | Related to what you're predicting | Irrelevant columns confuse the model |
| **Sufficient** | Enough rows (usually 1,000+) | Too few = model can't learn patterns |
| **Recent** | Not outdated | Old patterns may no longer apply |
| **Balanced** | Classes roughly equal (for classification) | Imbalanced data tricks the model |

> **Tip:** More data almost always beats a fancier algorithm. A simple model trained on 100,000 rows usually beats a complex model trained on 100 rows.

