## 3. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

### What is it?

EDA is your detective work. Before building anything, you **look around** and understand your data. You ask questions like:

- How many rows and columns do I have?
- Are there missing values?
- What does the data look like — min, max, average?
- Are there weird outliers?
- How do columns relate to each other?

Think of it like reading the instruction manual before assembling furniture.

### EDA Steps

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Load Data] --> B[Check shape\nrows × columns]
    B --> C[Check data types\nnumbers, text, dates?]
    C --> D[Look at first few rows]
    D --> E[Count missing values]
    E --> F[Descriptive stats\nmean, min, max, std]
    F --> G[Plot distributions\nhistograms]
    G --> H[Check correlations\nwhich columns move together?]
    H --> I[Spot outliers]
    I --> J[Write down what you found]
```

### Common EDA Questions & Tools

| Question | Tool / Chart |
|----------|-------------|
| What's the spread of values? | Histogram |
| Any relationship between two columns? | Scatter plot |
| Any outliers? | Box plot |
| How often does each category appear? | Bar chart |
| Which columns are most correlated? | Heatmap |

### Real-World Example

Pizza shop data after EDA reveals:
- Friday sales are 40% higher than Monday sales → **day of week** is important
- There are 12 rows where sales = 0 on holidays → might be store closed
- Weather temperature has a **0.6 correlation** with delivery orders → keep it!
- One row shows 9,999 pizzas sold → obvious **data entry error**, must fix

> EDA is not about fixing problems yet — just **finding** them. Fixing happens in the next step.

