## 4. Data Cleaning & Preprocessing

### What is it?

Raw data is messy. Real-world data has missing values, typos, inconsistent formats, and extreme outliers. Preprocessing turns raw data into something the model can actually learn from.

### The Cleaning Pipeline

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Raw Data] --> B[Handle Missing Values]
    B --> C[Fix Outliers]
    C --> D[Fix Inconsistent Values\neg. 'Male' vs 'male' vs 'M']
    D --> E[Convert Data Types\ndates, categories, booleans]
    E --> F[Encode Categorical Columns\ntext → numbers]
    F --> G[Feature Scaling\nbring all numbers to same range]
    G --> H[Feature Engineering\ncreate new useful columns]
    H --> I[Clean Data ✅]
```

### Handling Missing Values

| Strategy | When to use | Example |
|----------|-------------|---------|
| **Drop the row** | Very few missing rows | Only 5 out of 10,000 rows missing |
| **Fill with mean/median** | Numeric columns, missing randomly | Age column: fill with average age |
| **Fill with mode** | Categorical columns | City: fill with most common city |
| **Forward fill** | Time-series data | Yesterday's price fills today's gap |
| **Predict missing** | Important column, lots missing | Use another model to guess the value |

### Encoding Categorical Data

Models speak numbers, not words. You must convert text categories to numbers.

**One-Hot Encoding** (for unordered categories like Color):

```
Color: Red → [1, 0, 0]
Color: Blue → [0, 1, 0]
Color: Green → [0, 0, 1]
```

**Label Encoding** (for ordered categories like Size):

```
Size: Small → 1
Size: Medium → 2
Size: Large → 3
```

### Feature Scaling

Why? Because if one column goes from 0–1 and another from 0–1,000,000, the model will wrongly think the second column is more important.

| Method | Formula | Result Range | When to use |
|--------|---------|--------------|-------------|
| **Min-Max Scaling** | (x - min) / (max - min) | 0 to 1 | When you know the range |
| **Standard Scaling (Z-score)** | (x - mean) / std | -3 to +3 approx | Most common, default choice |

### Feature Engineering

Creating **new columns** from existing ones that help the model:

> **Example:** From a date column, create:
> - `day_of_week` (Monday=0, Sunday=6)
> - `is_weekend` (True/False)
> - `month` (1–12)
> - `is_holiday` (True/False)

These new columns are often more useful than the raw date.

