## 5. Train-Test Split

### What is it?

You can't grade your own homework. If the model trains on **all** the data, you have no way to know if it actually learned or just memorized.

So you split the data into:
- **Training set** — the model studies from this (learns patterns)
- **Test set** — the model is examined on this (never seen before!)

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[All Data\n100%] --> B[Training Set\n70–80%]
    A --> C[Test Set\n20–30%]
    B --> D[Model Trains Here]
    C --> E[Model is Tested Here]
    D --> F[Adjust & Improve]
    E --> G[Final Score]
```

### The Typical Split

| Split | Percentage | Purpose |
|-------|-----------|---------|
| Train | 70–80% | Model learns from this |
| Validation | 10–15% | Tune the model during development |
| Test | 10–20% | Final, untouched evaluation |

> **Golden Rule:** Never look at or use the test set until the very end. Treat it like an exam paper in a sealed envelope.

### Overfitting vs Underfitting

```
High training accuracy + Low test accuracy = OVERFITTING
(Model memorized, didn't learn)

Low training accuracy + Low test accuracy = UNDERFITTING
(Model is too simple, didn't learn enough)

High training accuracy ≈ High test accuracy = JUST RIGHT ✅
```

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Train the Model] --> B{Compare train vs test accuracy}
    B -- Train high, Test low --> C[Overfitting\nModel memorized the data]
    B -- Both low --> D[Underfitting\nModel too simple]
    B -- Both similarly high --> E[Good Fit ✅]
    C --> F[Fix: More data, simpler model,\nregularization, dropout]
    D --> G[Fix: More complex model,\nmore features, longer training]
```

### K-Fold Cross Validation

Instead of one split, you split the data K times and train+test on each fold. This gives a more reliable score.

```
Fold 1: [TEST] [train] [train] [train] [train]
Fold 2: [train] [TEST] [train] [train] [train]
Fold 3: [train] [train] [TEST] [train] [train]
Fold 4: [train] [train] [train] [TEST] [train]
Fold 5: [train] [train] [train] [train] [TEST]

Final Score = Average of all 5 scores
```

