## 6. Choosing the Right Model

### What is it?

There is no single "best" algorithm. Choosing the right model depends on:
- What type of problem you have (regression, classification, clustering)
- How much data you have
- How interpretable the result needs to be
- How fast the model needs to run

### Model Selection Flowchart

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[What kind of problem?] --> B{Labeled data\navailable?}
    B -- Yes --> C{Predict a number?}
    B -- No --> D[Unsupervised\nClustering: K-Means, DBSCAN]
    C -- Yes --> E[Regression]
    C -- No --> F[Classification]

    E --> E1[Linear Regression\nSimple, fast, interpretable]
    E --> E2[Decision Tree\nEasy to visualize]
    E --> E3[Random Forest\nAccurate, robust]
    E --> E4[XGBoost / LightGBM\nTop performer on structured data]
    E --> E5[Neural Network\nBest for images, text, audio]

    F --> F1[Logistic Regression\nSimple baseline]
    F --> F2[K-Nearest Neighbors\nSimple, intuitive]
    F --> F3[Support Vector Machine\nWorks in high dimensions]
    F --> F4[Random Forest\nVery reliable]
    F --> F5[XGBoost / LightGBM\nOften wins competitions]
    F --> F6[Neural Network\nBest for unstructured data]
```

### Model Cheat Sheet

| Model | Best For | Pros | Cons |
|-------|----------|------|------|
| **Linear Regression** | Predict numbers, simple relationship | Fast, explainable | Can't capture complex patterns |
| **Logistic Regression** | Binary yes/no classification | Simple, fast, probabilistic | Linear boundaries only |
| **Decision Tree** | Tabular data, explainable | Visual, intuitive | Overfits easily |
| **Random Forest** | Almost everything tabular | Accurate, handles missing values | Slow for very large data |
| **XGBoost / LightGBM** | Competitions, tabular data | Very accurate | Many hyperparameters to tune |
| **Neural Network** | Images, text, audio | Extremely powerful | Needs lots of data & compute |
| **K-Means** | Customer segmentation | Simple, scalable | You must specify K manually |

### Real-World Guidance

> **Start simple.** Always try Linear/Logistic Regression first. If it's not good enough, try Random Forest. If still not good enough, try XGBoost. Only use Neural Networks if you have > 10,000 rows and/or unstructured data (images, text).

