## 8. Evaluation Metrics

### What is it?

After training, you need to measure **how good** your model actually is. Different problems use different measurements.

### For Regression Problems (predicting numbers)

#### Mean Absolute Error (MAE)

> "On average, how far off is my prediction?"

$$MAE = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} |y_i - \hat{y}_i|$$

**Example:** Your pizza model predicted [80, 95, 60], actual was [82, 90, 65]

```
Errors: |80-82| + |95-90| + |60-65| = 2 + 5 + 5 = 12
MAE = 12 / 3 = 4 pizzas off on average
```

#### Mean Squared Error (MSE)

> "Same as MAE but big mistakes are punished much more."

$$MSE = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2$$

Squaring means an error of 10 counts 100 times more than an error of 1. Use when large errors are especially bad.

#### Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)

> "Same units as your original values — easier to understand."

$$RMSE = \sqrt{MSE}$$

If RMSE = 4.2 pizzas, your predictions are typically off by 4.2 pizzas.

#### R² Score (R-Squared)

> "What percentage of the variation in the data does my model explain?"

$$R^2 = 1 - \frac{\sum(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2}{\sum(y_i - \bar{y})^2}$$

| R² Value | Meaning |
|----------|---------|
| 1.0 | Perfect predictions |
| 0.9 | Explains 90% of variation — very good |
| 0.5 | Explains 50% — average |
| 0.0 | No better than always guessing the mean |
| < 0 | Worse than a dumb average — something is wrong |

---

### For Classification Problems (predicting categories)

#### Confusion Matrix

The foundation of all classification metrics. For a spam/not-spam classifier:

```
                  Predicted: Spam    Predicted: Not Spam
Actual: Spam         TP = 90              FN = 10
Actual: Not Spam     FP = 5               TN = 895
```

| Term | Meaning | Example |
|------|---------|---------|
| **TP** (True Positive) | Correctly said YES | Correctly flagged spam |
| **TN** (True Negative) | Correctly said NO | Correctly passed real email |
| **FP** (False Positive) | Said YES, was actually NO | Called real email spam (bad!) |
| **FN** (False Negative) | Said NO, was actually YES | Let spam through |

#### Accuracy

> "What % of all predictions were correct?"

$$Accuracy = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + TN + FP + FN}$$

```
Accuracy = (90 + 895) / (90 + 895 + 5 + 10) = 985 / 1000 = 98.5%
```

> ⚠️ **Warning:** Accuracy is misleading on imbalanced datasets!
> If 99% of emails are not spam, a model that always says "not spam" gets 99% accuracy — but is completely useless.

#### Precision

> "Of all the things I said were positive — how many actually were?"

$$Precision = \frac{TP}{TP + FP}$$

High precision = you rarely cry wolf.

#### Recall (Sensitivity)

> "Of all the real positives out there — how many did I catch?"

$$Recall = \frac{TP}{TP + FN}$$

High recall = you catch most of the real cases.

#### Precision vs Recall Tradeoff

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Catch more positives] --> B[Recall goes UP ↑]
    B --> C[But more false alarms]
    C --> D[Precision goes DOWN ↓]
    
    E[Be more strict] --> F[Precision goes UP ↑]
    F --> G[But miss some real ones]
    G --> H[Recall goes DOWN ↓]
```

> **When to prioritize what:**
> - **Medical diagnosis** → Prioritize Recall (don't miss sick patients)
> - **Spam filter** → Prioritize Precision (don't block important emails)

#### F1 Score

> "The balanced average of Precision and Recall."

$$F1 = 2 \times \frac{Precision \times Recall}{Precision + Recall}$$

Use F1 when you need a single metric that balances both.

### Summary: Which Metric to Use?

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Evaluation Metric Needed?] --> B{Type of Problem}
    B -- Regression --> C[MAE: easy to interpret\nRMSE: penalizes big errors\nR²: overall model quality]
    B -- Classification --> D{Classes balanced?}
    D -- Yes --> E[Accuracy is fine]
    D -- No --> F{What's more important?}
    F -- Catch all positives --> G[Use Recall]
    F -- Avoid false alarms --> H[Use Precision]
    F -- Balance both --> I[Use F1 Score]
```

